The paper deals with performance guarantees for a signal processing algorithm (orthogonal matching pursuit) in the presence of noise, which suggests that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT), Signal Processing (cs.SP), or Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The use of coherence-based analysis further supports the likelihood of cs.SP and cs.LG. The consideration of signal parameters such as dynamic range and sparsity suggests a numerical analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. Finally, the empirical validation of the results could also place the paper in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
